, it played a less important role in schools than later Demosthenian orations and fewer commentaries were written on it. The present study therefore meets the need for a critical commentary which examines linguistic, rhetorical and historical aspects. It also sheds light on the political situation on the eve of the decisive battle between Athens and the Macedon King Philip II.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aDemosthenes / Philippicae 4. 4aKommentar. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-DITION 2: BEST OF CLASSICAL STUDIESz9783110305609oZDB-23-DBA0 cprintz978311016930040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311088890440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110888904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110888904/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DBA  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014